  <fragment slot="intro">
    Dirty decks, driveways, house siding covered in algae and mold. Pressure washing restores the finish and prevents long-term damage. Fast results.
  </fragment>

  ## What Pressure Washing Does

  High-pressure water removes:
  - Algae and moss (common on shaded surfaces)
  - Mold and mildew (causes wood rot and respiratory issues)
  - Dirt, pollen, and weathering grime
  - Paint and stain prep (before recoating)

  On the Island, moss and algae grow fast due to rain and shade. Regular washing extends the life of wood, decks, driveways, and siding.

  ## Surfaces We Clean

  **Decks and patios** — 2,500–3,500 PSI (pounds per square inch). High pressure can damage wood if used wrong, so we use lower pressure with detergent for best results.

  **Driveways and concrete** — 3,000–3,500 PSI. Removes oil stains, algae, and weathering.

  **House siding** — 1,500–2,000 PSI. Gentle enough for vinyl and wood; we adjust for delicate surfaces like stucco.

  **Fence and deck boards** — Same as decks—we use appropriate pressure and angle to avoid gouging.

  **Gutters and downspouts** — Lower pressure to avoid bending metal.

  **Roof** — We do NOT pressure wash roofs. High pressure dislodges shingles and causes leaks. We recommend professional moss-removal products or manual cleaning instead.

  ## Pressure Washing vs. Soft Washing

  **Pressure washing** uses high PSI to blast away dirt. Good for concrete and heavily soiled surfaces. Can damage wood and delicate materials.

  **Soft washing** uses low pressure (under 500 PSI) with detergent to kill mold and algae. Better for wood, siding, and roofs. Takes longer but doesn't damage surfaces.

  We use the right technique for each surface.

  ## Cost & Timeline

  - Deck cleaning (per square foot): $0.15–$0.30
  - Driveway cleaning (per square foot): $0.10–$0.20
  - House siding (per square foot): $0.15–$0.25
  - Small deck (12x16): $200–$400
  - Small driveway (single car): $150–$300
  - Full house exterior: $800–$2,000

  Most jobs take 2–6 hours depending on size and condition.

  ## After Pressure Washing

  Plan to stain or seal decks and fences within a few weeks. The wood is clean and ready for finish. Pressure washing is the prep step for re-staining or resealing.

  ## Safety & Equipment

  Pressure washers are powerful. Using wrong technique or pressure can:
  - Gouge or splinter wood
  - Bend gutters and downspouts
  - Damage windows and seals
  - Cause slipping hazards
  - Injure skin (high-pressure water can cut)

  We have commercial-grade equipment, know the safe PSI for each surface, and have insurance.

  ## Prevention

  - Pressure wash decks and driveways every 2–3 years (or as needed).
  - Clean gutters before washing (dry debris comes off easier).
  - Treat algae-prone surfaces with algae preventive if they stay shaded.

